<subSubSection id="D7ABAFF8FFAA650B52BEFE13FE257ED0" pageId="11" pageNumber="10" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="9F0EFC73FFAA650B52BEFE13FC6178E9" blockId="11.[192,1440,495,649]" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">
<emphasis id="ADC52061FFAA650B52BEFE13FED97867" bold="true" box="[192,335,495,519]" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="58B187F0FFAA650B532AFE13FDF47867" authorityName="Harris and Armitage" authorityYear="2019" box="[340,610,495,519]" class="Insecta" family="Hydroptilidae" genus="Metrichia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="macdonaldi">
<emphasis id="ADC52061FFAA650B532AFE13FDF47867" box="[340,610,495,519]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">Metrichia macdonaldi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is placed in the nigritta group of 
<bibRefCitation id="FB208182FFAA650B5191FE0CFBEB7868" author="Flint, O. S., Jr." box="[1007,1149,496,520]" pageId="11" pageNumber="10" pagination="1 - 28" refId="ref16799" refString="Flint, O. S., Jr. 1972. Studies of Neotropical caddisflies, XIII. The genus Ochrotrichia for Mexico and Central America (Trichoptera: Hydroptilidae). Smithsonian Contributions to Zoology 118: 1 - 28." type="journal article" year="1972">Flint (1972)</bibRefCitation>
on the basis of the thick setal patches arising between the fifth and sixth abdominal segments and the pair of stout subapical hooks on the phallus. The new species has rectanguloid inferior appendages somewhat similar to that of 
<taxonomicName id="58B187F0FFAA650B52A1FDADFDA87809" authority="Bueno-Soria" authorityName="Bueno-Soria" box="[223,574,593,617]" class="Insecta" family="Hydroptilidae" genus="Metrichia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longitudinis">
<emphasis id="ADC52061FFAA650B52A1FDADFE087809" box="[223,414,593,617]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">M. longitudinis</emphasis>
Bueno-Soria
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="58B187F0FFAA650B5000FDADFBDE7809" authority="Souza and Santos" authorityName="Souza and Santos" box="[638,1096,593,617]" class="Insecta" family="Hydroptilidae" genus="Metrichia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pernambucana">
<emphasis id="ADC52061FFAA650B5000FDADFCC97809" box="[638,863,593,617]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">M. pernambucana</emphasis>
Souza and Santos
</taxonomicName>
, however the setal patches, and structure of the phallus, are much different in the new species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9F0EFC73FFAA650B52BEFD5EFE5D7EE0" blockId="11.[192,1440,674,1152]" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">
<emphasis id="ADC52061FFAA650B52BEFD5EFE9C78DA" bold="true" box="[192,266,674,698]" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">Male.</emphasis>
Length 
<quantity id="58495196FFAA650B530CFD5EFD9078D9" box="[370,518,674,698]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.75" metricValueMax="2.9" metricValueMin="2.6" pageId="11" pageNumber="10" unit="mm" value="2.75" valueMax="2.9" valueMin="2.6">2.6â€“2.9 mm</quantity>
. Head without modification. Antennae with 19 segments, middle segments slightly widening and flattened. Body and unmodified wings brown in alcohol. Abdominal segments with thick setal patches between segments V and VI, those on V much thicker than those of VI. Segments VII and VIII annular. Segment IX triangular in lateral view, anterior portion within segment VIII, posterior margin rounded dorsally; in ventral and dorsal views annular. Preanal appendage (cercus) thin in lateral view, apex rounded; in dorsal view short and lobate; dorsolateral hook narrow, widening to hatchet-like apex, posteriorly with several sclerotized processes; in dorsal view narrow over length, to widened, curved apex. Segment X membranous and rectangular laterally; in dorsal view thin and triangular, apex truncate. Inferior appendages in lateral view rectanguloid, narrowing anteriorly to rounded apex; in dorsal and ventral views wide basally, gradually narrowing anteriorly to rounded apex, series of peg-like setae on inner margins. Phallus widening basally and apically, apex in dorsal view with pair of spines subapically, inner spine short and stout, outer spine elongate and sharply curving at midlength, pair of short, stout spines basally; in lateral view two subapical spines evident, lowermost one straight, and upper one curving to acute upturned spike; ejaculatory duct thin extending anteriorly beyond curving spine.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9F0EFC73FFAA650B52BEFB64FE257ED0" blockId="11.[192,435,1176,1200]" box="[192,435,1176,1200]" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">
<emphasis id="ADC52061FFAA650B52BEFB64FEBA7ED0" bold="true" box="[192,300,1176,1200]" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">Female.</emphasis>
Unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
